# Rust Checks Before Committing

Before creating any git commit in this repository, always run
`cargo fmt` AND verify the tree builds and tests cleanly with **zero
warnings**. Stage any resulting changes as part of the same commit.
This keeps formatting noise and warning regressions out of subsequent
commits and avoids CI failures.

## Workflow

```bash
cargo fmt
cargo build --all-targets 2>&1 | tee /tmp/build.log | tail
cargo test --all-targets 2>&1 | tee /tmp/test.log | tail
git add -A
git commit -m "..."
```

If `cargo fmt` touches files unrelated to your change, include them in
the same commit rather than creating a separate formatting commit —
the project's history treats formatting as part of the logical change
that introduced it.

## Verification

All three checks MUST pass on the final tree before committing:

1. `cargo fmt --check` exits 0. If not, run `cargo fmt` and re-stage.
2. `cargo build --all-targets` produces no lines starting with
   `warning:`. The default rustc lint set plus the project's
   `[lints.rust]` config in `Cargo.toml` is the baseline — the tree
   is expected to build clean under it, and any new warning your
   change introduces must be fixed before committing.
3. `cargo test --all-targets` produces no lines starting with
   `warning:` and all tests pass.

### Quick one-liner

```bash
cargo fmt --check \
  && ! cargo build --all-targets 2>&1 | grep -q '^warning:' \
  && ! cargo test --all-targets 2>&1 | grep -q '^warning:'
```

If any of these fail, fix the underlying cause before committing.
Do NOT silence warnings with blanket `#[allow(...)]` just to pass
this check — only silence a lint when the code genuinely needs to
violate it (e.g. test-only code that must stay independent of
production helpers) and add a comment or doc explaining why.

## Scope note

This rule covers the default `cargo build` / `cargo test` warning
surface. It does NOT require `cargo clippy --all-targets` to be
clean: the tree has a large pre-existing clippy-warning backlog
that is being reduced opportunistically rather than as a hard
precommit gate. If your change happens to touch a file whose clippy
warnings you want to address, do so in the same commit; otherwise
leave the backlog alone.
